<%# Phase 27 v2 spec 05 — `/games` is a single shelves-by-letter
    layout. The display-mode switcher and the three per-mode partials
    (`_grid_mode` / `_list_mode` / `_shelves_by_letter_mode`) are gone;
    the page renders one stack of shelves top-to-bottom:

      1. Page title `games` + `[+]`.
      2. Filter row (spec 06 reworks the row's internal layout).
      3. Recently-played shelf (only when at least one game has
         `played_at` set).
      4. Hairline.
      5. Genres outer shelf (one sub-shelf per non-empty genre,
         heading labels per `GenresHelper#genre_display_name` —
         IGDB-verbatim except for the cosmetic renames in
         `GENRE_DISPLAY_RENAMES`).
      6. Hairline.
      7. Bundles outer shelf (one tile per non-empty bundle, alphabetical;
         clicking a tile opens the bundles-modal pane).
      8. Hairline.
      9. Letter shelves (one shelf per non-empty letter A..Z, then
         `#` bucket at the end if non-empty).

    Phase 27 follow-up (2026-05-17) — the legacy top-of-page "bundles"
    shelf (10 most-recent bundles) was merged into the Bundles outer
    shelf below; they were two views onto the same model and the
    Collection→Bundle consolidation made the duplication redundant.

    Phase 27 v2 spec 06 — the listing partition (shelves 3–10 above)
    is wrapped in `<turbo-frame id="games_listing">` so the
    `games-filter` Stimulus controller can re-fetch the frame on
    chip toggle without re-rendering the filter row itself or
    triggering a full page navigation.

    Each shelf carries the `steam-shelf` Stimulus controller for
    drag-scroll + mouse-wheel-to-horizontal scroll, with the project's
    themed slim scrollbar (6 px on both axes — see the global
    `::-webkit-scrollbar` rules in `app/assets/tailwind/application.css`).

    Phase 14 §1 polish (2026-05-10) — the inline IGDB type-ahead
    `_add_form` partial was retired. The H1 carries a `[+]`
    bracketed link that opens the layout-level IGDB-search modal
    (`shared/_igdb_search_modal`). 2026-05-17 — the previous global
    `i` keybind was removed in the legacy-keyboard-shortcut sweep;
    the `[+]` link is now the only entry point. %>
<% content_for(:title, t("games.index.title")) %>

<%# 2026-05-19 — Live refresh subscription. Every Game create / update /
    destroy broadcasts a Turbo `refresh` signal to the `"games"` stream
    (see `after_*_commit` hooks on `Game`). On receipt, Turbo morph-
    refreshes the page in place so the shelves below (recently-played +
    genres + bundles + letter buckets) reflect newly-added rows AND
    `Igdb::SyncGame#call`'s async backfill of title / genres / cover.
    Layout meta `turbo-refresh-method=morph` + `turbo-refresh-scroll=
    preserve` keep scroll position. %>
<%= turbo_stream_from "games" %>

<%# 2026-05-17 polish (revised) — `/games` shares one horizontal column
    with the rest of the page. The chrome wrapper (`<main>`) in
    `application.html.erb` already carries the canonical 12 px
    horizontal padding; this view does NOT introduce its own
    `max-width` clamp or viewport break-out. Title row, filter row,
    and shelves Turbo Frame all sit inside the same content container
    so their left and right edges line up with the navbar nav links
    (and the footer copy) — i.e. 12 px from each viewport edge.

    The previous `max-width: 1100px` wrapper around the title + filter
    band, plus the `.games-shelves-fullwidth` viewport break-out
    around the shelves frame, were removed in favor of this single
    aligned column. Per-shelf horizontal scroll on overflow is
    unchanged — each `.shelf` row keeps its own `overflow-x: auto`. %>
<div>
  <div style="display: flex; align-items: baseline; gap: 8px; margin-bottom: 6px;">
    <div class="dot-list">
      <h1><%= t("games.index.heading") %></h1>
      <%# 2026-05-18 — unified omnisearch chrome. The `[+]` button now
          opens the shared `_omnisearch_modal` in `:game_index` mode
          (Mac-style big-bold input + `[close]` footer) instead of the
          old `_igdb_search_modal` partial whose chrome (small input +
          `[cancel]` link) diverged visually from the other two
          omnisearch surfaces (`/games SPACE /` and the bundle modal
          `[+]`). The endpoint and per-row IGDB `[add]` / `[update]`
          contract are unchanged — `/games/search` still backs the
          modal and `_search_results` still renders the rows; only the
          surrounding chrome is unified. %>
      <%= render(BracketedLinkComponent.new(
            label: t("common.actions.add_short"),
            href: "#",
            data: {
              controller: "modal-trigger",
              action: "click->modal-trigger#open",
              modal_trigger_target_id_value: "omnisearch-modal-games-index"
            }
          )) %>
    </div>
  </div>

  <%# Phase 27 v2 spec 06 — single compact filter band. All chips
      default to CHECKED; URL `/games` (no `?filters=`) means "full
      list". The Stimulus controller mounted on the row itself manages
      chip toggles, the cascade, and the Turbo Frame refresh. The
      row stays OUTSIDE the `games_listing` frame so it does not
      re-render per chip click. The row uses `justify-content:
      space-between` internally so the left (status + ownership) chip
      group sits flush against the content container's left edge and
      the right (platform) chip group sits flush against its right
      edge — aligning with the navbar / footer chrome. %>
  <%= render Game::FilterRowComponent.new(
        checked_tokens:         @checked_tokens,
        request_path:           games_path
      ) %>

  <%# Phase 27 v2 spec 06 — Turbo Frame wraps the listing partition.
      Filter chip clicks point the frame at the new URL via Stimulus;
      the frame fetches and morphs in the new contents without a full
      navigation. The frame id (`games_listing`) is declared in the
      FilterRowComponent's `data-games-filter-frame-id-value` for the
      controller to target — frame lookup is by id, so the frame may
      live anywhere in the document as long as the id is unique. %>
  <%# 2026-05-17 — `games_listing` frame ALWAYS renders a visible body.
      The previous outer `if has_any_content` wrapper let the frame
      collapse to a comment-only / whitespace-only body when every shelf
      bucket was empty (e.g. `?filters=` with zero results, or
      `?filters=...,played` against a library where no game has
      `played_at` set). Turbo Frame fetches against a body that
      degenerates to whitespace tripped the "Content missing" fallback
      in some browsers — the user saw the literal `Content missing`
      string below the filter row instead of an empty-state message.
      Explicit empty-state copy inside the frame keeps the frame body
      non-empty so Turbo's frame-missing detection never fires AND
      gives the user a useful "no games match this filter" hint. %>
  <%= turbo_frame_tag "games_listing" do %>
    <%# 2026-05-18 — `has_any_content` no longer gates the bundles
        shelf. The bundles partial renders UNCONDITIONALLY below so the
        heading-row `[+]` create button is always available even when
        the user has zero games AND zero bundles. The "no games match
        this filter" empty-state copy still renders for the other
        listing partitions (recently played + genres + letter shelves)
        when none of them have content. %>
    <% has_any_listing_content = @recently_played.any? ||
                                 @genres_for_shelf.any? ||
                                 @letter_buckets.any? %>

    <% if @recently_played.any? %>
      <%= render(::ShelfComponent.new(
            heading: t("games.index.recently_played_heading"),
            show_count: false,
            heading_level: :h2,
            row_gap: "8px"
          )) do %>
        <% @recently_played.each do |game| %>
          <%= render(Game::GameTileComponent.new(game: game, variant: :grid)) %>
        <% end %>
      <% end %>
    <% end %>

    <%# Phase 27 §01c-v2 — Genres outer shelf. One sub-shelf per non-
        empty genre, alphabetical. Empty buckets hidden. %>
    <% if @genres_for_shelf.any? %>
      <hr class="hairline">
      <%= render "games/genres_shelf", genres: @genres_for_shelf %>
    <% end %>

    <%# Bundles outer shelf — one tile per non-empty bundle.
        2026-05-18 — rendered UNCONDITIONALLY when no filter is active
        (`params[:filters].nil?`) so the heading-row `[+]` create button
        is always available from `/games`. When a filter IS active AND
        the result set is empty, hide the entire bundles section
        (heading + count chip + `[+]` + shelf row) — otherwise the
        zero-count heading reads as visual noise next to the
        "no games match this filter." copy. Matches the same
        hide-when-empty pattern that the genres + letter shelves use in
        filtered state (they gate on `.any?` above and below). %>
    <% if @bundles_for_shelf.any? || params[:filters].nil? %>
      <hr class="hairline">
      <%= render "games/bundles_for_shelf", bundles: @bundles_for_shelf %>
    <% end %>

    <%# Phase 27 v2 spec 05 — Letter shelves. One `<section>` per non-
        empty letter; `#` bucket renders LAST when present. %>
    <% if @letter_buckets.any? %>
      <hr class="hairline">
      <%= render "games/letter_shelves", buckets: @letter_buckets %>
    <% end %>

    <% unless has_any_listing_content %>
      <p class="text-muted" style="margin: 16px 0 0;"><%= t("games.index.no_matches") %></p>
    <% end %>
  <% end %>
</div>

<%# 2026-05-18 — `/`-keyed omnisearch modal (`:games_search` mode).
    Opened by the `/ search` page action in `config/keybindings.yml`
    (page_actions.games_index → open_modal_by_id target:
    "omnisearch-modal-games-search"). Hits /games/omnisearch and
    returns local games + bundles + IGDB as separate sections. %>
<%= render Search::OmnisearchModalComponent.new(
      mode: :games_search,
      dialog_id: "omnisearch-modal-games-search",
      url: omnisearch_games_path,
      placeholder: t("games.omnisearch.placeholder"),
      results_frame_id: "omnisearch_results_games_search"
    ) %>

<%# 2026-05-18 — `[+]` `:game_index` omnisearch modal. IGDB-only
    add-from-IGDB flow. Hits `/games/search` (the existing endpoint
    rendering `_search_results`, which already wraps its body in a
    `<turbo-frame id="igdb_search_results">` so the per-row
    `[add]` / `[update]` contract is preserved unchanged); only the
    surrounding chrome is unified with the other two omnisearch
    surfaces. The frame id MUST match the partial's own
    `turbo_frame_tag` so the controller-driven `src` swap lands in
    the right frame. %>
<%= render Search::OmnisearchModalComponent.new(
      mode: :game_index,
      dialog_id: "omnisearch-modal-games-index",
      url: search_games_path,
      placeholder: t("games.search.placeholder_igdb"),
      results_frame_id: "igdb_search_results"
    ) %>
